LXVII. ¹ Trepidare; ad arcem oppidi, ubi siqua et scuta erant, praesidium hostium, &c.] This is the punctuation of Kritzius, which I take for correct3 as also his interpretation, which is, that nam and erat are understood in the first member of the sentence, viz„ nam ad arcem, &c., praesidium host. erat. Ad arcem in sensu idem est atque in arce, he says, and then refers to Livy and Handius, on Latin Par- ticles. Trepidare semper intransitivo sensu idem valet atque in tre- pidatione esse, nunquam autem significat cum festinatione aliquem locum petere. Fallitur enim Cottius, qui ad hanc sententiam proban- dam his Livii locis utitur, 9, 37, 9, Maximam partem ad arma trepi- dantes coedes oppressit, &03 in Altero autem loco, 23, 16, 12, Dis· cursu trepidat ad prima siqua, &c. He makes ad the same as apud in those places. Tres igitur, continues he, causae trepidandi ciam affe- rantur, praes. host. ad arcem, portae clausae, mulierum ferocia, ὅτε. The rest Ι have given in the beginning of this note.—C.

² An casu ita evenerit.] Plutarch, in his life of Marius, tells us, that Turpilius was guilty of no treachery, and that his escaping at this time was owing, not to chance, but purely to the regard the people of Vaga had for him, on account of his lenity and gentle government.—M.
